          "prompt_html": "<h1>NOTE COMPLETION 40</h1><p><strong>Questions 31 - 40</strong></p><p>Complete the notes.</p><p>Use <strong>NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS</strong> for each answer.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Sports Psychology Lecture Notes - The Chimp Paradox by Prof. Steve Peters</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Brain</strong><br>- Seven separate connected parts, of which three considered the ‘psychological brain’: frontal, limbic, parietal.<br><strong>Peters' Mind Management Model</strong><br><strong>Chimp</strong><br>- Seen as <blank data-qid=\"q31\"/>, not always in synergy with the Human part of our brain.<br>- Responsible for negative emotions and highlights inadequacies based on own <blank data-qid=\"q32\"/> and paranoia.<br>- Can simultaneously be your ally or your <blank data-qid=\"q33\"/>.<br><strong>Human and Computer</strong><br>- The Human section of the psychological brain obeys rules, creating <blank data-qid=\"q34\"/> with the Chimp.<br>- The Computer: the storage system for the Chimp and Human, which can function autonomously as a <blank data-qid=\"q35\"/>.<br>- The emotions controlled by the Chimp cannot be removed, but we can regulate them and our <blank data-qid=\"q36\"/> by employing various techniques.<br><blank/><br><strong>Famous Athletes</strong><br><strong>Pendleton</strong><br>- Peters' methods show her how to re-frame events and turn negative thoughts into <blank data-qid=\"q37\"/> .<br>- Was essential to her success, Peters' methods eventually translated into multiple <blank data-qid=\"q38\"/> for Pendleton.<br><strong>O'Sullivan</strong><br>- Snooker player: naturally good at his sport since childhood.<br>- Has had several periods of <blank data-qid=\"q39\"/> throughout his life.<br><strong>Link between mind and body</strong><br>- Can be positive or negative.<br>- In a professional sporting context means making it, or abandoning the <blank data-qid=\"q40\"/>.</td></tr></tbody></table>",
